Q18: Labels clutter the vis. making it impossible to share information without some dynamic element. Also, through exposure to networks in popular media, many audiences tend to be distracted by pretty colors, interesting shapes, etc., and the more "scientifically interesting" ideas often are not possible to express in a visualization, though it tends to be expected
Q19: better support for interactive networks (simpler than learning D3)

Q18: quickly isolated key network features that can be highlighted in a large network
Grasping large structure
Large nets w. high densiy
Many vertices / many edges produce an uninterpretable "hairball."  Tools are either not powerful or unintuitive and ill-documented.
Reduction of information, avoiding the "hairball", optimizing layout for human perception
Q19: Have a layout developed by cognitive scientists that is best for dealing with human perception (e.g. plot connected nodes closer together, minimize crossings of links, avoid obtuse angles when links are crossed,..)

Q18: Projections on subsapaces or vectors, as for example the full set of eigenvectors.
Q19: Projections on subspaces.

Q18: I think the biggest challenges deal with communicating structural/functional information using only different color and size for objects. This is a real challenge when the number of nodes is larger than a few hundred, because the density of links often introduces "visual noise". / As an expert in the field of multilayer networks, I think that another big challenge is in finding new algorithms and visualization techniques to achieve the same goal while working in a multilayer environment, where information to show grows exponentially with the number of layers involved.
Q19: I would like to have a tool allowing for *interactivity* like in D3, but easy to use as Gephi (that in turn has many drawbacks). it would be great to have a tool like this usable within R or python. Now, I generally have to invent ad-hoc solutions to port my (often multilayer) networks to Gephi and from there export to SigmaJS, in order to obtain a result with a bit of interactivity. I thought about D3, but no way to learn a new language just for this task, it costs time and effort and I already know quite well R and python, although I code my simulations mainly in C++. I think that visualization obstacles are related to different drawbacks in different languages: R is great but awful and not indicated for heavy simulations, python is quite simple but graphically poor, and other graphical tools require pre-processing in order to be used. I explored the possibility of using Julia, because performances are good as C++, but unfortunately the graphical environment is still far from being optimal as in R, and there is still need for a library/package allowing to build interactive visualizations, where one can access multivariate information about nodes and links just by clicking on them.
